value.value: A small cavity bounded by an epithelium.
A hole in a tissue.
A tissue whose predominant feature is extracellular matrix which may or may not be highly hydrated or calcified.
Ossified structure that is predominantly extracellular matrix and forms part of the support system of the body.
Bone that is preformed in cartilage.
Bone that forms directly from mesenchyme.
An endochondral bone that forms within tendenous or ligamentous matrix.
Dense connective tissue made primarily of type II collagen.
A strap of predominantly extracellular matrix connecting two bones.
A strap of predominantly extracellular matrix connecting a muscle to a bone.
A sheet of extracellular matrix.
An anatomical group whose component structures share a common function.
Multicellular anatomical structure with largely bona fide boundary that transduces some sensory stimulus to the nervous system.
Fluid anatomical entity containing cells.
A multi-tissue structure that produces a secretion for use elsewhere in the body.
A gland that releases its secretion through a duct.
A gland that releases its secretion directly into the bloodstream, or equivalent for an invertebrate.
Acellular anatomical structure whose predominant constituent is keratin.
Acellular anatomical structure whose predominant constituent is chitin.
The region of the organism associated with the visceral organs.
The region of the body containing the brain and mouth.
The region of the body connecting the head and the body.
An external caudal extension of the body.
Epithelium derived from mesenchyme.
An epithelial structure capable of allowing fluid flow.
An epithelial pouch with a single opening.
A group of connected epithelial tubes with a single portal.
A network of interlinking epithelial tubes.
A closed epithelium with a lumen.
A tissue composed of myoblasts or muscle cells.
Tissue composed predominantly of neurons.
A structure whose morphology or state of differentiation will change during normal development.
A post-embryonic juvenile form which will undergo metamorphosis to become the adult.
An embryonic anatomical structure undergoing apoptosis.
An embryonic entity that displays a physiological function but whose strucuture is not yet fully formed.
Embronic structure that contains stem cellsr that may contribute to its future development or maintenance or to its future development or maintenance of another tissue.
An embryonic anatomical entity that will turn into one or more other anatomical entities, perhaps with other anatomical entities, later in development.
A group of neurons, usually outside the CNS, which relay neuronal signals.
A localised domain of predominantly neuronal tissue in the central nervous system.
A group of neurons that provides a nervous supply.
A complex of interconnecting nerves.
A fasciculated bundle of neuron projections, largely or completely lacking synapses.
A tissue composed of striated muscle cells.
A tissue composed of smooth muscle cells.
A tissue composed of cardiac muscle cells.
A ring of smooth muscle cells whose contraction closes the opening of the ring.
A ring of striated muscle cells whose contraction closes the opening of the ring.
A group of not-yet-terminally-differentiatied cells that can pack in three dimensions.
Mesenchyme with little extracellular matrix.
Cell condensation that is an aggregation of mesenchymal cells that are committed to differentiate into chondroblasts and chondrocytes.
